A large part of this is not starting.
A novel-length story goes one of two ways. You write out a draft and as you revise/edit, you add in all the ideas that you'd have never thought of at the start. Or, you write episodically and hope to hell you don't make a drastic u-turn in the middle as something even more awesome occurs to you as a plot twist.
You never get those parts which really are the reward if you don't grind through the novice levels.

Anonymous Wed 30 Mar 2022 13:11:19 No.46549020 Report
Quoted By:
>>46543420
The current era in my opinion makes it easiest for the reader to get into the story, so to speak, without any huge cultural differences that have to be written around or explained before you can get into the action. And showing cultural differences so that the reader grasps them immediately without having to stop and infodump at the reader is a very difficult trick to pull off. Not every writer can do it.

In any era you do have to get the reader invested in a world where /hmofa/ stories can take place and explain the presence of nonhuman sapients, or at least allude to it. You have a few choices, and some work better in some eras than others: magical portals to a world where anthros are the dominant life forms, permitting cultural content and trade. They were created by magic ("a wizard did it"). Genetic engineering (only really fits in post-WWII). Interuniversal portals and interuniversal travel created by high technology and SCIENCE! rather than magic (also needs to be set in an era where this is plausible for storytelling purposes). It is possible to mix and match tech levels and historical eras but it's very difficult to pull off well. Howard Waldrop has done it, though without anthros.

Harems were functional in ancient times because they resulted in laywomen being uplifted into semi-royalty. Kings/chiefs had queens/consorts, but they were often in arranged marriages, or had matters of their own to attend. If they didn't, they were essentially slaves to their lords anyway; monogamous relationships as super-emotional partnerships are more a product of industrialization and suburbanization. I'm not some anti-monogamy edgelord, mind you; I like the evolution of modern romance. They existed in ye olden thymes, but they were very different from what we know of today. No, every man did not have a harem, but women cracking down on their husbands lousing around can be chronicled back as far as ancient Rome. Of course, women were poisoning their husband's for many more reasons than just punishment; there were assets at stake, and a with Rome being a civil society under rule of law, there were mechanisms in place for the transfer of property. Then came the prenuptial agreement.
Then there's Henry the VIII, but that's another historical can of worms. I'm playing fast and loose with the history because I lack the autism, but an emotionally conceived and loyal harem can be a wonderful thing. Besides, it goes both ways; I'm imagining an Amazon warrior queen salazzle with a harem of salandit (reminds me of gnolls), and I'm kind of surprised some furry hasn't writen that yet.
